{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-js","path":"/how-to-update-intel-nic-firmware","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>You should update your NIC cause newer is always better right? Right!</p>\n<!-- more -->\n<p>I honestly haven't found any good guides to run through this process so I thought I'd write my own.</p>\n<p>I will be updating my Intel I350 T4 NIC that I got in Christmas 2014. I will be focused on updating through EFI rather than Windows or DOS. But the instructions should apply to both.</p>\n<p><strong>1</strong> Download the latest firmware from <a href=\"https://downloadcenter.intel.com/download/19186/Intel-Ethernet-Connections-Boot-Utility-Preboot-images-and-EFI-Drivers\">Intel</a>. At the time of writing it was 20.4.1</p>\n<p><strong>2</strong> Run <strong>PREBOOT.EXE</strong> to unpack its files. You will need the <em>BootUtil</em> folder under <em>APPS</em></p>\n<p><strong>3</strong> Boot into your EFI, Windows or DOS</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 347px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/efb4febc9a7b4ca17ce21159c9782426/c8500/boot.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 81.69014084507043%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Boot\"\n        title=\"Boot\"\n        src=\"/static/efb4febc9a7b4ca17ce21159c9782426/c8500/boot.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/efb4febc9a7b4ca17ce21159c9782426/53f68/boot.png 213w,\n/static/efb4febc9a7b4ca17ce21159c9782426/c8500/boot.png 347w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 347px) 100vw, 347px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p><strong>4</strong> For EFI, change paths by entering the path into the EFI shell. I am using a USB and it was mounted under fs0.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 405px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/aab86a6abc1a19e38b8881b91a9f9f81/b6699/fs0.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 58.68544600938967%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"FS0\"\n        title=\"FS0\"\n        src=\"/static/aab86a6abc1a19e38b8881b91a9f9f81/b6699/fs0.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/aab86a6abc1a19e38b8881b91a9f9f81/53f68/fs0.png 213w,\n/static/aab86a6abc1a19e38b8881b91a9f9f81/b6699/fs0.png 405w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 405px) 100vw, 405px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p><strong>5</strong> Depending on where you are updating once again, run the executable under your operating system folder to be shown a list of network adapters available</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 647px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/c17584146774df2b19fe1fda4ddf9c17/f9e62/running-command.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 59.62441314553991%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"running command\"\n        title=\"running command\"\n        src=\"/static/c17584146774df2b19fe1fda4ddf9c17/f9e62/running-command.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/c17584146774df2b19fe1fda4ddf9c17/53f68/running-command.png 213w,\n/static/c17584146774df2b19fe1fda4ddf9c17/df70d/running-command.png 425w,\n/static/c17584146774df2b19fe1fda4ddf9c17/f9e62/running-command.png 647w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 647px) 100vw, 647px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p><strong>6</strong> If a NIC is saying it cannot be flashed (but you know it can be), enable flash using the command:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"shell-session\"><pre style=\"counter-reset: linenumber NaN\" class=\"language-shell-session line-numbers\"><code class=\"language-shell-session\"><span class=\"token output\">BootUtil -NIC=1 -FLASHENABLE</span></code><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"line-numbers-rows\" style=\"white-space: normal; width: auto; left: 0;\"><span></span></span></pre></div>\n<p>Where -NIC is the port number. Reboot when done and go to the next step.</p>\n<p><strong>7</strong> You can choose to update a particular NIC or all at once using:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"shell-session\"><pre style=\"counter-reset: linenumber NaN\" class=\"language-shell-session line-numbers\"><code class=\"language-shell-session\"><span class=\"token output\">BootUtil -UP=PXE -ALL (Assumes input file is bootimg.flb)</span></code><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"line-numbers-rows\" style=\"white-space: normal; width: auto; left: 0;\"><span></span></span></pre></div>\n<p>Or specifying the file using:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"shell-session\"><pre style=\"counter-reset: linenumber NaN\" class=\"language-shell-session line-numbers\"><code class=\"language-shell-session\"><span class=\"token output\">Bootutil -UP=PXE -ALL -FILE=BOOTIMG.FLB (explicit user specified file)</span></code><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"line-numbers-rows\" style=\"white-space: normal; width: auto; left: 0;\"><span></span></span></pre></div>\n<p><strong>8</strong> You will be prompted to save create a restore image for your NIC before updating. It is probably best to do this in case something goes wrong :P</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 649px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/42d7cd94181307127fa61db6fdefb1c0/1bcec/updating.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 36.61971830985916%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Updating\"\n        title=\"Updating\"\n        src=\"/static/42d7cd94181307127fa61db6fdefb1c0/1bcec/updating.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/42d7cd94181307127fa61db6fdefb1c0/53f68/updating.png 213w,\n/static/42d7cd94181307127fa61db6fdefb1c0/df70d/updating.png 425w,\n/static/42d7cd94181307127fa61db6fdefb1c0/1bcec/updating.png 649w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 649px) 100vw, 649px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p><strong>9</strong> After the update, reboot and you are done!</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 641px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/7b1af0192c3ccf107acd3f79e33ff367/243e6/update-complete.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 60.093896713615024%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Update complete\"\n        title=\"Update complete\"\n        src=\"/static/7b1af0192c3ccf107acd3f79e33ff367/243e6/update-complete.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/7b1af0192c3ccf107acd3f79e33ff367/53f68/update-complete.png 213w,\n/static/7b1af0192c3ccf107acd3f79e33ff367/df70d/update-complete.png 425w,\n/static/7b1af0192c3ccf107acd3f79e33ff367/243e6/update-complete.png 641w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 641px) 100vw, 641px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n        decoding=\"async\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<h2 id=\"conclusion\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#conclusion\" aria-label=\"conclusion permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Conclusion</h2>\n<p>Did I notice a speed/latency difference? Nope :P</p>\n<p>If you look at the release notes for each version, there doesn't appear to be any improvements, if at all, for any devices. Intel is just adding more support for their newer devices and operating system support for others.</p>","timeToRead":2,"excerpt":"You should update your NIC cause newer is always better right? Right! I honestly haven't found any good guides to run through this process…","fileAbsolutePath":"/home/runner/work/calvin.me/calvin.me/master/posts/2016/2016-01-23-how-to-update-intel-nic-firmware/index.md","frontmatter":{"title":"How to Update Firmware on an Intel NIC","categories":["Networking"],"tags":["intel"],"thumbnail":{"childImageSharp":{"gatsbyImageData":{"layout":"fixed","backgroundColor":"#080808","images":{"fallback":{"src":"/static/d467612f43bfda947015617f0808be98/ccc8a/thumbnail.png","srcSet":"/static/d467612f43bfda947015617f0808be98/ccc8a/thumbnail.png 150w,\n/static/d467612f43bfda947015617f0808be98/67d4a/thumbnail.png 300w","sizes":"150px"},"sources":[{"srcSet":"/static/d467612f43bfda947015617f0808be98/3554d/thumbnail.webp 150w,\n/static/d467612f43bfda947015617f0808be98/c437f/thumbnail.webp 300w","type":"image/webp","sizes":"150px"}]},"width":150,"height":150}}}}}},"pageContext":{"filter":"/^.*\\/\\d{4}-\\d{2}-\\d{2}-how-to-update-intel-nic-firmware\\/.*$/"}},"staticQueryHashes":[]}